{"title_page": "Moral psychology", "text_new": "'''Moral psychology''' is a field of study in both [[philosophy]] and [[psychology]]. Historically, the term \"moral psychology\" was used relatively narrowly to refer to the study of [[moral development]].<ref name=\"Haidt&Kesebir2010\">{{cite book |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Kesebir |first2=Selin |editor1-last=Fiske |editor1-first=S |editor2-last=Gilbert |editor2-first=D |editor3-last=Lindzey |editor3-first=G |title=Handbook of Social Psychology |date=2010 |publisher=Wiley |location=Hoboken NJ |pages=797-832 |edition=5 |url=http://courses.washington.edu/ccab/Haidt%20&%20Kesebir%20on%20morality%20-%20HB%20Soc%20Psych%202010.pdf |chapter=Morality}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Moral Psychology|last=Lapsley|first=Daniel K.|date=1996|publisher=Westview Press|isbn=978-0-8133-3032-7|series=Developmental psychology series|location=Boulder, Colorado|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/moralpsychology0000laps}}</ref> Moral psychology eventually came to refer more broadly to various topics at the intersection of [[ethics]], psychology, and [[philosophy of mind]].<ref>{{citation | last=Doris | first=John | last2=Stich | first2= Stephen | year=2008 | title=Moral Psychology: Empirical Approaches | journal=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy | editor-first= Edward N. | editor-last=Zalta | url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/moral-psych-emp/ | ref=harv| publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Jackson | editor-first=Frank | editor-last2=Smith | editor-first2=Michael | last=Wallace | first=R. Jay | title=The Oxford Handbook of Contemporary Philosophy | chapter=Moral Psychology | date=November 29, 2007 | pages=86\u2013113 | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H4sIErz7KUcC&pg=PA86 | publisher=OUP Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-923476-9 | quote=Moral psychology is the study of morality in its psychological dimensions}}</ref><ref name=\"Ellemers2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Ellemers |first1=Naomi |last2=van der Toorn |first2=Jojanneke |last3=Paunov |first3=Yavor |last4=van Leeuwen |first4=Thed |title=The Psychology of Morality: A Review and Analysis of Empirical Studies Published From 1940 Through 2017 |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |volume=23 |issue=4 |date=18 January 2019 |pages=332\u2013366 |doi=10.1177/1088868318811759 |pmid=30658545 |pmc=6791030 |language=en |issn=1088-8683}}</ref> Some of the main topics of the field are moral judgment, [[moral reasoning]], moral sensitivity, [[moral responsibility]], moral motivation, moral identity, moral action, [[moral development]], [[moral diversity]], [[moral character]] (especially as related to [[virtue ethics]]), [[altruism]], [[psychological egoism]], [[moral luck]], moral forecasting, moral emotion, [[affective forecasting]], and moral disagreement.{{sfn|Doris|Stich|2008|loc=\u00a71}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Teper|first1=R.|last2=Inzlicht|first2=M.|last3=Page-Gould|first3=E.|year=2011|title=Are we more moral than we think?: Exploring the role of affect in moral behavior and moral forecasting|journal=Psychological Science|volume=22|issue=4|pages=553\u2013558|doi=10.1177/0956797611402513|pmid=21415242|citeseerx=10.1.1.1033.5192}}</ref>\n\nToday, moral psychology is a thriving area of research spanning many disciplines,<ref>Doris & Stich (2008), \u00a71.</ref> with major bodies of research on the biological,<ref name=\"Sevinc2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Sevinc |first1=Gunes |last2=Spreng |first2=R. Nathan |last3=Soriano-Mas |first3=Carles |title=Contextual and Perceptual Brain Processes Underlying Moral Cognition: A Quantitative Meta-Analysis of Moral Reasoning and Moral Emotions |journal=PLoS ONE |date=4 February 2014 |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=e87427 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0087427|pmid=24503959 |pmc=3913597 |bibcode=2014PLoSO...987427S }}</ref><ref name=\"Moll2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Moll |first1=Jorge |last2=Zahn |first2=Roland |last3=de Oliveira-Souza |first3=Ricardo |last4=Krueger |first4=Frank |last5=Grafman |first5=Jordan |title=The neural basis of human moral cognition |journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience |date=October 2005 |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=799\u2013809 |doi=10.1038/nrn1768|pmid=16276356 }}</ref> cognitive/computational<ref name=\"KleimanWeiner2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Kleiman-Weiner |first1=Max |last2=Saxe |first2=Rebecca |last3=Tenenbaum |first3=Joshua B. |title=Learning a commonsense moral theory |journal=Cognition |date=October 2017 |volume=167 |pages=107\u2013123 |doi=10.1016/j.cognition.2017.03.005 |pmid=28351662 |hdl=1721.1/118457 |hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\"Cushman2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Cushman |first1=Fiery |title=Action, Outcome, and Value |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |date=16 July 2013 |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=273\u2013292 |doi=10.1177/1088868313495594 |pmid=23861355 }}</ref><ref name=\"Crockett2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Crockett |first1=Molly J. |title=Models of morality |journal=Trends in Cognitive Sciences |date=August 2013 |volume=17 |issue=8 |pages=363\u2013366 |doi=10.1016/j.tics.2013.06.005 |pmid=23845564 |pmc=3925799 }}</ref> and cultural<ref name=\"Henrich2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Henrich |first1=Joseph |last2=Boyd |first2=Robert |last3=Bowles |first3=Samuel |last4=Camerer |first4=Colin |last5=Fehr |first5=Ernst |last6=Gintis |first6=Herbert |last7=McElreath |first7=Richard |last8=Alvard |first8=Michael |last9=Barr |first9=Abigail |last10=Ensminger |first10=Jean |last11=Henrich |first11=Natalie Smith |last12=Hill |first12=Kim |last13=Gil-White |first13=Francisco |last14=Gurven |first14=Michael |last15=Marlowe |first15=Frank W. |last16=Patton |first16=John Q. |last17=Tracer |first17=David |title=\"Economic man\" in cross-cultural perspective: Behavioral experiments in 15 small-scale societies |journal=Behavioral and Brain Sciences |date=22 December 2005 |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=795\u2013815 |doi=10.1017/S0140525X05000142 |pmid=16372952 |url=https://authors.library.caltech.edu/2278/1/HENbbs05.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"Purzycki2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Purzycki |first1=Benjamin Grant |last2=Apicella |first2=Coren |last3=Atkinson |first3=Quentin D. |last4=Cohen |first4=Emma |last5=McNamara |first5=Rita Anne |last6=Willard |first6=Aiyana K. |last7=Xygalatas |first7=Dimitris |last8=Norenzayan |first8=Ara |last9=Henrich |first9=Joseph |title=Moralistic gods, supernatural punishment and the expansion of human sociality |journal=Nature |date=10 February 2016 |volume=530 |issue=7590 |pages=327\u2013330 |doi=10.1038/nature16980|pmid=26863190 |url=https://pure.au.dk/ws/files/96835878/nature16980.pdf |bibcode=2016Natur.530..327P }}</ref> basis of moral judgment and behavior, and a growing body of research on moral judgment in the context of artificial intelligence.<ref name=\"Awad2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Awad |first1=Edmond |last2=Dsouza |first2=Sohan |last3=Kim |first3=Richard |last4=Schulz |first4=Jonathan |last5=Henrich |first5=Joseph |last6=Shariff |first6=Azim |last7=Bonnefon |first7=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |last8=Rahwan |first8=Iyad |title=The Moral Machine experiment |journal=Nature |date=24 October 2018 |volume=563 |issue=7729 |pages=59\u201364 |doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0637-6 |pmid=30356211 |bibcode=2018Natur.563...59A |hdl=10871/39187 |hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\"Bonnefon2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Bonnefon |first1=J.-F. |last2=Shariff |first2=A. |last3=Rahwan |first3=I. |title=The social dilemma of autonomous vehicles |journal=Science |date=23 June 2016 |volume=352 |issue=6293 |pages=1573\u20131576 |doi=10.1126/science.aaf2654 |pmid=27339987 |bibcode=2016Sci...352.1573B |arxiv=1510.03346 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe origins of moral psychology can be traced back to early philosophical works, largely concerned with moral education, such as by [[Plato]] and [[Aristotle]] in Ancient Greece,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carr |first1=David |title=Metaphysics and methods in moral enquiry and education: Some old philosophical wine for new theoretical bottles |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=26 August 2014 |volume=43 |issue=4 |pages=500\u2013515 |doi=10.1080/03057240.2014.943167}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lewis |first1=Paul |title=In defence of Aristotle on character: toward a synthesis of recent psychology, neuroscience and the thought of Michael Polanyi |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=June 2012 |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=155\u2013170 |doi=10.1080/03057240.2012.668005}}</ref> as well as from the [[Confucianism#Social_morality_and_ethics|Confucian]] tradition.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fengyan * |first1=Wang |title=Confucian thinking in traditional moral education: key ideas and fundamental features |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=December 2004 |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=429\u2013447 |doi=10.1080/0305724042000327984}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Murray |first1=Judson B. |title=Educating human nature: \u2018nature\u2019 and \u2018nurture\u2019 in early Confucian moral education |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=December 2012 |volume=41 |issue=4 |pages=509\u2013527 |doi=10.1080/03057240.2012.721759}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wei |first1=Tan Tai |title=Some Confucian Insights and Moral Education |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=January 1990 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201337 |doi=10.1080/0305724900190104}}</ref> Empirical studies of moral judgment go back at least as far as the 1890s with the work of [[Frank Chapman Sharp]],<ref name=\"Sharp1898\">{{cite journal |last1=Sharp |first1=Frank Chapman |title=An Objective Study of Some Moral Judgments |journal=The American Journal of Psychology |date=January 1898 |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=198\u2013234 |doi=10.2307/1411759 |jstor=1411759 }}</ref> coinciding with the development of psychology as a discipline separate from philosophy. Since at least 1894, philosophers and psychologists attempted to empirically evaluate the morality of an individual,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=May |first1=Mark A. |last2=Hartshorne |first2=Hugh |title=Objective Methods of Measuring Character |journal=The Pedagogical Seminary and Journal of Genetic Psychology |date=March 1925 |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=45\u201367 |doi=10.1080/08856559.1925.10532317}}</ref><ref name=\"Pittel1966\">{{cite journal |last1=Pittel |first1=Stephen M. |last2=Mendelsohn |first2=Gerald A. |title=Measurement of moral values: A review and critique. |journal=Psychological Bulletin |date=1966 |volume=66 |issue=1 |pages=22\u201335 |doi=10.1037/h0023425}}</ref> especially attempting to distinguish adults from children in terms of their judgment, but these efforts failed because they \"attempted to quantify how much morality an individual had\u2014a notably contentious idea\u2014rather than understand the individual's psychological representation of morality\".<ref name=\"Wendorf2001\">{{cite journal|last=Wendorf|first=Craig A|year=2001|title=History of American morality research, 1894\u20131932|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247411256|journal=History of Psychology|volume=4|issue=3|pages=272\u2013288|doi=10.1037/1093-4510.4.3.272|via=}}</ref>{{rp|page=284}}\n\n{{Quotebox|align=right|width=40%|quoted=1|quote=[I]f you said that you studied moral psychology in the 1980s, then you probably studied the development of moral reasoning. You didn\u2019t need to agree with Kohlberg on any particular claim, but you lived and worked on land that Kohlberg had cleared.|source=Jonathan Haidt<ref name=\"Haidt2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |title=Moral psychology for the twenty-first century |journal=Journal of Moral Education |date=September 2013 |volume=42 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013297 |doi=10.1080/03057240.2013.817327}}</ref>{{rp|page=282}}}}\n\nIn most introductory psychology courses, students learn about moral psychology by studying the psychologist [[Lawrence Kohlberg]],<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Kohlberg |first=Lawrence |title=The development of modes of moral thinking and choice in the years 10 to 16. |date=1958 |degree=PhD |location=Chicago |oclc=1165315}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |title=The Measurement of Moral Judgment |last1=Colby |first1=Anne |last2=Kohlberg |first2=Lawrence |date=1987 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-32565-3 |series=Standard Issue Scoring Manual |volume=2 |location=Cambridge |pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Socialization Theory and Research|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofsocial0000gosl|chapter-url-access=registration|last=Kohlberg|first=L.|date=1969|publisher=Rand McNally|editor-last=Goslin|editor-first=David|location=Chicago|pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookofsocial0000gosl/page/347 347\u2013480]|chapter=Stage and sequence: The cognitive development approach to socialization}}</ref> who proposed a highly influential [[Kohlberg's stages of moral development|theory of moral development]], developed throughout the 1950s and 1960s. This theory was built on [[Jean Piaget|Piaget]]'s observation that children develop intuitions about justice that they can later articulate. Kohlberg proposed [[Lawrence Kohlberg's stages of moral development|six stages]] broken into 3 categories of moral reasoning that, he believed to be universal to all people in all cultures.<ref>{{Citation|last=Kohlberg|first=Lawrence|chapter=1. Stages of moral development as a basis for moral education|date=1971-01-31|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442656758|doi=10.3138/9781442656758-004|title=Moral Education}}</ref> The increasing sophistication of justice-based reasoning was taken as a sign of development. Moral cognitive development, in turn, was assumed to be a necessary (but not sufficient) condition for moral action.<ref name=\"Kohlberg1977\">{{cite journal |last1=Kohlberg |first1=Lawrence |last2=Hersh |first2=Richard H. |title=Moral development: A review of the theory |journal=Theory Into Practice |date=1977 |volume=16 |issue=2 |pages=53\u201359 |doi=10.1080/00405847709542675}}</ref>\n\nBut researchers using the Kohlberg model found a gap between what people said was most moral and actions they took. In response, Augusto Blasi proposed his self-model{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} that links ideas of moral judgment and action through moral commitment. Those with moral goals central to the self-concept are more likely to take moral action, as they feel a greater obligation to do so. Those who are motivated will attain a unique moral identity.<ref name=\"Hardy, S. A. 2011\">{{cite journal|last1=Hardy|first1=S. A.|last2=Carlo|first2=G.|year=2011|title=Moral identity: What is it, how does it develop, and is it linked to moral action?|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229948988|journal=Child Development Perspectives|volume=5|issue=3|pages=212\u2013218|doi=10.1111/j.1750-8606.2011.00189.x|via=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publication of a pair of landmark papers in 2001,<ref name=\"Haidt2001\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|date=October 2001|title=The Emotional Dog and Its Rational Tail|url=http://fitelson.org/confirmation/reasoning_adler_rips.pdf#page=1036|journal=Psychological Review|volume=108|issue=4|pages=814\u2013834|doi=10.1037/0033-295X.108.4.814|pmid=11699120|ref=harv|via=|citeseerx=10.1.1.620.5536}}</ref><ref name=\"Greene2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=J. D. |last2=Sommerville |first2=R Brian |last3=Nystrom |first3=Leigh E |last4=Darley |first4=John M. |last5=Cohen |first5=Jonathan D |title=An fMRI Investigation of Emotional Engagement in Moral Judgment |journal=Science |date=14 September 2001 |volume=293 |issue=5537 |pages=2105\u20132108 |doi=10.1126/science.1062872}}</ref> there was a surge in interest in moral psychology across a broad range of subfields of psychology, with interest shifting away from developmental processes towards a greater emphasis on social, cognitive, affective and neural processes involved in moral judgment.<ref name=\"Haidt&Kesebir2010\" /><ref name=\"Ellemers2019\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen Priva |first1=Uriel |last2=Austerweil |first2=Joseph L. |title=Analyzing the history of Cognition using Topic Models |journal=Cognition |date=February 2015 |volume=135 |pages=4\u20139 |doi=10.1016/j.cognition.2014.11.006}}</ref>\n\n==Methods==\n[[File:Trolley problem.png|thumb|The trolley problem, a commonly-used moral dilemma in psychological research]]\n\nPhilosophers, psychologists and researchers from other fields have created various methods for studying topics in moral psychology, with empirical studies dating back to at least the 1890s.<ref name=\"Wendorf2001\" /> The methods used in these studies include moral dilemmas such as the [[trolley problem]],<ref name=\"Sharp1898\" /><ref name=\"Greene2001\" /> structured interviews and surveys as a means to study moral psychology and its development, as well as the use of economic games,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Story |first1=Giles W. |last2=Vlaev |first2=Ivo |last3=Metcalfe |first3=Robert D. |last4=Crockett |first4=Molly J. |last5=Kurth-Nelson |first5=Zeb |last6=Darzi |first6=Ara |last7=Dolan |first7=Raymond J. |title=Social redistribution of pain and money |journal=Scientific Reports |date=30 October 2015 |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=15389 |doi=10.1038/srep15389|pmid=26515529 |pmc=4626774 |bibcode=2015NatSR...515389S }}</ref> neuroimaging,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moll |first1=Jorge |last2=de Oliveira-Souza |first2=Ricardo |last3=Eslinger |first3=Paul J. |last4=Bramati |first4=Ivanei E. |last5=Mour\u00e3o-Miranda |first5=Jana\u0131\u0301na |last6=Andreiuolo |first6=Pedro Angelo |last7=Pessoa |first7=Luiz |title=The Neural Correlates of Moral Sensitivity: A Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging Investigation of Basic and Moral Emotions |journal=The Journal of Neuroscience |date=1 April 2002 |volume=22 |issue=7 |pages=2730\u20132736 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.22-07-02730.2002 |pmid=11923438 |pmc=6758288}}</ref> and studies of natural language use.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sagi |first1=Eyal |last2=Dehghani |first2=Morteza |title=Measuring Moral Rhetoric in Text |journal=Social Science Computer Review |date=31 October 2013 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=132\u2013144 |doi=10.1177/0894439313506837}}</ref>\n\n===Interview techniques===\nIn 1963, Lawrence Kohlberg presented an approach to studying differences in moral judgment by modeling evaluative diversity as reflecting a series of developmental stages (\u00e0 la Jean Piaget). [[Lawrence Kohlberg's stages of moral development]] are:<ref name=\"higheststage\">{{cite journal | last=Kohlberg | first=Lawrence | title=The Claim to Moral Adequacy of a Highest Stage of Moral Judgment | journal=Journal of Philosophy | volume=70 | year=1973 | pages=630\u2013646 | doi=10.2307/2025030 | issue=18 | jstor=2025030 }}</ref>\n# Obedience and punishment orientation\n# Self-interest orientation\n# Interpersonal accord and conformity\n# Authority and social-order maintaining orientation\n# Social contract orientation\n# Universal ethical principles\n\nStages 1 and 2 are combined into a single stage labeled \"pre-conventional\", and stages 5 and 6 are combined into a single stage labeled \"post-conventional\" for the same reason; psychologists can consistently categorize subjects into the resulting four stages using the \"Moral Judgement Interview\" which asks subjects why they endorse the answers they do to a standard set of moral dilemmas.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Survey instruments===\nBetween 1910 and 1930, in the United States and Europe, several morality tests were developed to classify subjects as fit or unfit to make moral judgments.<ref name=Wendorf2001/><ref name=\"Verplaetse2008\">{{cite journal | last=Verplaetse | first=Jan | title=Measuring the moral sense: morality tests in continental Europe between 1910 and 1930 | journal= Paedagogica Historica | volume=44 | issue=3 | year=2008 | pages=265\u2013286 | doi=10.1080/00309230701722721}}</ref> Test-takers would classify or rank standardized lists of personality traits, hypothetical actions, or pictures of hypothetical scenes. As early as 1926, catalogs of personality tests included sections specifically for morality tests, though critics persuasively argued that they merely measured intelligence or awareness of social expectations.<ref name=\"Wendorf2001\" />\n\nMeanwhile, Kohlberg inspired a new wave of morality tests. The [[Defining Issues Test]] (dubbed \"Neo-Kohlbergian\" by its constituents) scores relative preference for post-conventional justifications,<ref>{{cite book|title=Development in Judging Moral Issues|last=Rest|first=James R.|date=1979|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-0-8166-0891-1|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> and the Moral Judgment Test scores consistency of one's preferred justifications.<ref name=\"Lind1978\">{{cite book|title=Sozialisation und Moral|last=Lind|first=Georg|publisher=Beltz|year=1978|isbn=9783407511348|editor-last=Portele|editor-first=G.|location=Weinheim|pages=171\u2013201|language=German|trans-title=Socialization and Morality|chapter=Wie misst man moralisches Urteil? Probleme und alternative M\u00f6glichkeiten der Messung eines komplexen Konstrukts|trans-chapter=How do you measure moral judgment? Problems and alternative ways of measuring a complex construct|oclc=715635639}}</ref><ref name=\"Lind2008\">{{cite book |last1=Lind |first1=Georg |editor1-last=Fasko |editor1-first=Daniel Jr |editor2-last=Willis |editor2-first=Wayne |title=Contemporary Philosophical and Psychological Perspectives on Moral Development and Education |date=2008 |publisher=Hampton Press |pages=185-220 |chapter=The meaning and measurement of moral judgment competence: A dual-aspect model}}</ref> Both treat evaluative ability as similar to [[IQ]] (hence the single score), allowing categorization by high score vs. low score.\n\nThe [[Jonathan Haidt#Moral Foundations Theory|Moral Foundations Questionnaire]]<ref name=\"Graham2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Nosek |first2=Brian A. |last3=Haidt |first3=Jonathan |last4=Iyer |first4=Ravi |last5=Koleva |first5=Spassena |last6=Ditto |first6=Peter H. |title=Mapping the moral domain. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=2011 |volume=101 |issue=2 |pages=366\u2013385 |doi=10.1037/a0021847|pmc=3116962 }}</ref> is based on moral intuitions consistent across cultures: care/harm, fairness/cheating, loyalty/betrayal, authority/subversion, and sanctity/degradation. The questions ask respondents to rate various considerations in terms of how relevant they are to the respondent's moral judgments. The purpose of the questionnaire is to measure the degree to which people rely upon each of the five moral intuitions (which may coexist). The first two foundations cluster together with liberal political orientation and the latter three cluster with conservative political orientation.<ref name=\"Graham2009\">{{cite journal|last=Graham|first=Jesse|last2=Haidt|first2=Jonathan|last3=Nosek|first3=Brian A.|year=2009|title=Liberals and conservatives rely on different sets of moral foundations|url=http://projectimplicit.net/nosek/papers/GHN2009.pdf|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=96|issue=5|pages=1029\u20131046|doi=10.1037/a0015141|pmid=19379034|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Graham2013\">{{cite book | last1=Graham | first1=J. | last2=Haidt | first2=J. | last3=Koleva | first3=S. | last4=Motyl | first4=M. | last5=Iyer | first5=R. | last6=Wojcik | first6=S. | last7=Ditto | first7=P.H. | title=Moral Foundations Theory: The pragmatic validity of moral pluralism | journal=Advances in Experimental Social Psychology | volume=47 | year=2013 | pages=55\u2013130 | url=http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GHKMIWD.inpress.MFT.AESP.pdf | doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-407236-7.00002-4 | isbn=9780124072367 | access-date=2015-01-11 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731065520/http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GHKMIWD.inpress.MFT.AESP.pdf | archive-date=2017-07-31 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Evolutionary origins==\n[[File:IMG-20180218-WA0095.jpg|thumb|Cooperative behavior has been observed in many nonhuman animals.]]\n{{Main|Evolution of morality}}\n{{Also|Evolutionary ethics}}\n\nAccording to Haidt,<ref name=\"Haidt2013\" /> the belief that morality is not innate was one of the few theoretical commitments uniting many of the prominent psychologists studying morality in the twentieth century. A substantial amount of research in recent decades has focused on the evolutionary origins of various aspects of morality.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Sinnott-Armstrong |editor1-first=Walter |title=Moral Psychology, Volume 1: The Evolution of Morality: Adaptations and Innateness |date=2007 |isbn=9780262693547 |url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/moral-psychology-volume-1}}</ref><ref name=\"Brosnan2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Brosnan |first1=S. F. |last2=de Waal |first2=F. B. M. |title=Evolution of responses to (un)fairness |journal=Science |date=18 September 2014 |volume=346 |issue=6207 |pages=1251776 |doi=10.1126/science.1251776 |pmid=25324394 |pmc=4451566 }}</ref><ref name=\"Tomasello2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Tomasello |first1=Michael |last2=Vaish |first2=Amrisha |title=Origins of Human Cooperation and Morality |journal=Annual Review of Psychology |date=3 January 2013 |volume=64 |issue=1 |pages=231\u2013255 |doi=10.1146/annurev-psych-113011-143812|pmid=22804772 |hdl=10161/13649 |hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\"Hare2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Hare |first1=Brian |title=Survival of the Friendliest: Evolved via Selection for Prosociality |journal=Annual Review of Psychology |date=3 January 2017 |volume=68 |issue=1 |pages=155\u2013186 |doi=10.1146/annurev-psych-010416-044201 |pmid=27732802 }}</ref> In ''Unto Others: the Evolution and Psychology of Unselfish Behavior'' (1998), [[Elliott Sober]] and [[David Sloan Wilson]] demonstrated that diverse moralities could evolve through [[group selection]].<ref name=\"Sober&Wilson1999\">{{cite book |last1=Sober |first1=Elliot |last2=Wilson |first2=David Sloan |title=Unto others : the evolution and psychology of unselfish behavior |date=1999 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674930476}}</ref> In particular, they dismantled the idea that [[natural selection]] will favor a homogeneous population in which all creatures care only about their own personal welfare and/or behave only in ways which advance their own personal reproduction.<ref>{{cite book|title=Unto Others: The Evolution and Psychology of Unselfish Behavior|last=Sober|first=Elliott|last2=Wilson|first2=David Sloan|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1998|isbn=9780674930469|location=Cambridge|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/untoothersevolut00sobe}}</ref> Tim Dean has advanced the more general claim that moral diversity would evolve through [[frequency-dependent selection]] because each moral approach is vulnerable to a different set of situations which threatened our ancestors.<ref name=Dean2012>{{cite journal|title= Evolution and moral diversity |author=Dean, Tim |journal=Baltic International Yearbook of Cognition, Logic and Communication|year=2012|volume=7|doi=10.4148/biyclc.v7i0.1775|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Topics and Theories==\n\n===Moral identity===\n{{Main|Moral identity}}\nMoral identity is a concept within moral psychology referring to the importance of morality to a person\u2019s identity, typically construed as either a trait-like individual difference, or set of chronically accessible schemas.<ref name=\"Hardy, S. A. 2011\" /><ref name=\"Hardy&Carlo2011\" >{{cite book |last1=Hardy |first1=Sam A. |last2=Carlo |first2=Gustavo |editor1-last=Schwartz |editor1-first=Seth J. |editor2-last=Luyckx |editor2-first=Koen |editor3-last=Vignoles |editor3-first=Vivian L. |title=Handbook of identity theory and research |date=2011 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-1-4419-7988-9 |pages=495-513 |chapter=Moral Identity}}</ref> Moral identity is theorized to be one of the key motivational forces connecting moral reasoning to moral behavior,<ref name=\"Hardy&Carlo2011\" /> as suggested by a 2016 meta-analysis reporting that moral identity is positively associated with moral behavior.<ref name=\"Hertz&Krettenauer2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Hertz |first1=Steven G. |last2=Krettenauer |first2=Tobias |title=Does Moral Identity Effectively Predict Moral Behavior?: A           Meta-Analysis |journal=Review of General Psychology |date=1 June 2016 |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=129\u2013140 |doi=10.1037/gpr0000062}}</ref>\n\n===Moral values===\n{{See also|Moral foundations theory|Theory of Basic Human Values}}\n\nPsychologist [[Shalom H. Schwartz|Shalom Schwartz]] defines individual values as \"conceptions of the desirable that guide the way social actors (e.g.organisational leaders, policymakers, individual persons) select actions, evaluate people an events, and explain their actions and evaluations.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schwartz|first1=S. H.|year=1999|title=A Theory of Cultural Values and Some Implications for Work |url=http://130.18.86.27/faculty/warkentin/SecurityPapers/Merrill/Schwartz1999_APIR48_1_CulturalValues.pdf |journal=Applied Psychology: An International Review |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=23\u201347 |doi=10.1080/026999499377655|via=}}</ref> Cultural values form the basis for social norms, laws, customs and practices. While individual values vary case by case (a result of unique life experience), the average of these values point to widely held cultural beliefs (a result of shared cultural values).\n\nKristiansen and Hotte<ref name=\u201cKristiansen&Hotte1996\u201d>{{cite conference|last1=Kristiansen|first1=Connie M|last2=Hotte|first2=Alan M|date=1996|title=Morality and the self: Implications for the when and how of value-attitude-behavior relations|conference=The Psychology of Values: The Ontario Symposium on Personality and Social Psychology|publisher=Erlbaum Hillsdale, NJ|volume=8|pages=77\u2013105}}</ref> reviewed many research articles regarding people's values and attitudes and whether they guide behavior. With the research they reviewed and their own extension of Ajzen and Fishbein's [[theory of reasoned action]], they conclude that value-attitude-behavior depends on the individual and their moral reasoning. They also pointed out that there are such things as good values and bad values. Good values are those that guide our attitudes and behaviors and allow us to express and define ourselves. It also involves the ability to know when values are appropriate in response to the situation or person that you are dealing with. Bad values on the other hand are those that are relied on so much that it makes you unresponsive to the needs and perspectives of others.\n\nAnother issue that Kristiansen and Hotte discovered through their research was that individuals tended to \"create\" values to justify their reactions to certain situations, which they called the \"value justification hypothesis\".<ref name=\u201cKristiansen&Hotte1996\u201d /> Their theory is comparable to Jonathan Haidt's [[Social intuitionism|social intuitionist theory]],<ref name=\"Haidt2001\" /> where individuals justify their intuitive emotions and actions through post-hoc moral reasoning.\n\nKristiansen and Hotte also found that independent selves had actions and behaviors that are influenced by their own thoughts and feelings, but [[Interdependent]] selves have actions, behaviors and self-concepts that were based on the thoughts and feelings of others. Westerners have two dimensions of emotions, activation and pleasantness. The Japanese have one more, the range of their interdependent relationships. Markus and Kitayama found that these two different types of values had different motives. Westerners, in their explanations, show self-bettering biases. Easterners, on the other hand, tend to focus on \"other-oriented\" biases.<ref name=\u201cKristiansen&Hotte1996\u201d />\n\n====Moral Foundations Theory====\n{{Main|Moral foundations theory}}\nMoral foundations theory, first proposed in 2004 by Jonathan Haidt and Craig Joseph,<ref name=\"Haidt2004\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|author2=Craig Joseph|title=Intuitive ethics: how innately prepared intuitions generate culturally variable virtues|journal=Daedalus|date=Fall 2004|volume=133|issue=4|pages=55\u201366|url=http://faculty.virginia.edu/haidtlab/articles/haidt.joseph.2004.intuitive-ethics.pub035.pdf|doi=10.1162/0011526042365555|access-date=2012-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909124829/http://faculty.virginia.edu/haidtlab/articles/haidt.joseph.2004.intuitive-ethics.pub035.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> attempts to explain the origins of and variation in human moral reasoning on the basis of innate, modular foundations. Notably, Moral Foundations Theory has been used to describe the difference between the moral foundations of political liberals and political conservatives.<ref name=\"Haidt&Graham2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Graham |first2=Jesse |title=When Morality Opposes Justice: Conservatives Have Moral Intuitions that Liberals may not Recognize |journal=Social Justice Research |date=23 May 2007 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=98\u2013116 |doi=10.1007/s11211-007-0034-z}}</ref><ref name=\"Graham2009\" /> Haidt and Joseph expanded on previous research done by Shweder and his three ethics theory.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> Shweder's theory consisted of three moral ethics: the ethic of autonomy, the ethic of community, and the ethic of divinity.<ref name=\"Shweder1997\">{{cite book |last1=Shweder |first1=Richard |last2=Much |first2=Nancy |last3=Mahapatra |first3=Manamohan |last4=Park |first4=Lawrence |editor1-last=Brandt |editor1-first=Allan |editor2-last=Rozin |editor2-first=Paul |title=Morality and Health |publisher=Routledge |pages=119\u2013169 |date=1997 |chapter=The \"big three\" of morality (autonomy, community, divinity) and the \"big three\" explanations of suffering.}}</ref> Haidt and Graham took this theory and extended it to discuss the five psychological systems that more specifically make up the three moral ethics theory. These Five Foundations of Morality and their importance vary throughout each culture and construct virtues based on their emphasized foundation. \nThe five psychological foundations are:\n* Harm/care, which starts with the sensitivity to signs of suffering in offspring and develops into a general dislike of seeing suffering in others and the potential to feel compassion in response.\n* Fairness/reciprocity, which is developed when someone observes or engages in reciprocal interactions. This foundation is concerned with virtues related to fairness and justice. \n* Ingroup/loyalty, which constitutes recognizing, trusting, and cooperating with members of one's ingroup as well as being wary of members of other groups.\n* Authority/respect, which is how someone navigates in a [[Hierarchical equations of motion|hierarchal]] ingroups and communities.\n* Purity/sanctity, which stems from the emotion of disgust that guards the body by responding to elicitors that are biologically or culturally linked to disease transmission.\nThe five foundations theory are both a [[Psychological nativism|nativist]] and cultural-psychological theory. Modern moral psychology concedes that \"morality is about protecting individuals\" and focuses primarily on issues of justice (harm/care and fairness/reciprocity).<ref name=\"Haidt&Graham2007\" />{{rp|page=99}} Their research found that \"justice and related virtues\u2026make up half of the moral world for liberals, while justice-related concerns make up only one fifth of the moral world for conservatives\".<ref name=\"Haidt&Graham2007\" />{{rp|page=99}} Liberals value harm/care and fairness/reciprocity significantly more than the other moralities, while conservatives value all five equally.\n\n===Moral virtues===\nPiaget and Kohlberg both developed stages of development to understand the timing and meaning of moral decisions. They were interested in placing people into moral categories or stages of development instead of identifying how each individual's views and behaviors are affected by their background and personality. In 2004, D. Lapsley and D. Narvaez outlined how [[social cognition]] explains aspects of moral functioning.<ref>{{cite book|title=Moral Development, Self, and Identity|last1=Lapsley|first1=Daniel K.|last2=Narvaez|first2=Darcia|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2004|isbn=978-1-135-63233-5|location=|pages=189\u2013212|chapter=A social-cognitive approach to the moral personality|ref=harv|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=q054AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA189}}</ref> The social cognitive approach to personality has six critical resources of moral personality: cognition, self-processes, affective elements of personality, changing social context, lawful situational variability, and the integration of other literature. Lapsley and Narvaez suggest that moral values and actions stem from more than our virtues and are controlled by a set of self-created [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] (cognitive structures that organize related concepts and integrate past events). They claim that schemas are \"fundamental to our very ability to notice dilemmas as we appraise the moral landscape\" and that over time, people develop greater \"moral expertise\".{{Sfn|Lapsley|Narvaez|2004|p=197}}\n\n==== Triune ethics theory ====\n{{Main|Triune ethics Meta-theory}}\nThe triune ethics meta-theory (TEM) has been proposed by Darcia Narvaez as a [[metatheory]] that highlights the relative contributions to moral development of [[biological inheritance]] (including human evolutionary [[adaptations]]), environmental influences on neurobiology, and the role of culture.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite journal|last=Narvaez|first=Darcia|date=March 1, 2008|title=Triune ethics: The neurobiological roots of our multiple moralities|url=https://www3.nd.edu/~dnarvaez/TriuneEthicsWord.htm|journal=New Ideas in Psychology|volume=26|issue=1|pages=95\u2013119|doi=10.1016/j.newideapsych.2007.07.008|issn=0732-118X|via=|citeseerx=10.1.1.152.4926}}</ref> TET proposes three basic mindsets that shape ethical behavior: self-protectionism (a variety of types), engagement, and imagination (a variety of types that are fueld by protectionism or engagement). A mindset influences perception, affordances, and rhetorical preferences. Actions taken within a mindset become an ethic when they trump other values. Engagement and communal imagination represent optimal human functioning that are shaped by the evolved developmental niche (evolved nest) that supports optimal psychosocial neurobiological development.<ref name=\"Narv\u00e1ez, Darcia 2009\">{{cite book |title=Neurobiology and the Development of Human Morality: Evolution, Culture and Wisdom |last1=Narvaez |first1=Darcia  |publisher=WWNorton|year=2014|isbn=978-0393706550}}</ref>  Based on worldwide anthropological research (e.g., Hewlett and Lamb's Hunter-Gatherer Childhoods), Narvaez uses small-band hunter-gatherers as a baseline for the evolved nest and its effects. The empirical support for the link between early experience and the development of triune ethics dispositions (\"moral temperament\") is accumulating from studies of young children and of adults.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Moral reasoning and development===\n{{main|Moral reasoning|Moral development}}\n{{see also|Moral education|Values education}}\nMoral development and reasoning are two overlapping topics of study in moral psychology that have historically received a great amount of attention, even preceding the influential work of Piaget and Kohlberg.<ref name=\"Wendorf2001\" /> Moral reasoning refers specifically to the study of how people think about right and wrong and how they acquire and apply moral rules.<ref name=\"Pizarro2007a\">{{cite book |last1=Pizarro |first1=David A. |editor1-last=Baumeister |editor1-first=Roy F |editor2-last=Vohs |editor2-first=Kathleen F |title=Encyclopedia of Social Psychology |date=2007 |publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc. |isbn=9781412956253 |pages=591\u2013592 |chapter=Moral Reasoning|doi=10.4135/9781412956253.n352 }}</ref> Moral development refers more broadly to age-related changes in thoughts and emotions that guide moral beliefs, judgments and behaviors.<ref name=\"Barnett2007\">{{cite book |last1=Barnett |first1=Mark A. |editor1-last=Baumeister |editor1-first=Roy F |editor2-last=Vohs |editor2-first=Kathleen D |title=Encyclopedia of Social Psychology |date=2007 |publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc. |isbn=9781412956253 |pages=587 |chapter=Moral Development|doi=10.4135/9781412956253.n349 }}</ref>\n\n====Kohlberg's stage theory====\n{{main|Lawrence Kohlberg's stages of moral development}}\nJean Piaget, in watching children play games, noted how their rationales for cooperation changed with experience and maturation.<ref name=\"Piaget1948\">{{cite book |last1=Piaget |first1=Jean |title=The Moral Judgment of the Child |date=1948 |publisher=Free Press |url=https://www.burmalibrary.org/docs20/Piaget-moral_judgment_of_the_child-en-ocr-tu.pdf}}</ref> He identified two stages, [[wikt:heteronomous|heteronomous]] (morality centered outside the self) and autonomous (internalized morality). [[Lawrence Kohlberg|Lawerence Kohlberg]] sought to expand Piaget's work. His cognitive developmental theory of moral reasoning dominated the field for decades. He focused on moral development as one's progression in the capacity to reason about justice. Kohlberg's interview method included hypothetical moral dilemmas or conflicts of interest (most notably, the [[Heinz dilemma]]). He proposed six stages and three levels of development (claiming that \"anyone who interviewed children about dilemmas and who followed them longitudinally in time would come to our six stages and no others).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Psychology of Moral Development: The Nature and Validity of Moral Stages|last=Kohlberg|first=Lawrence|publisher=Harper & Row|year=1984|isbn=978-0-06-064761-2|series=Essays on Moral Developent|volume=2|location=|pages=195}}</ref> At the Preconventional level, the first two stages included the punishment-and-obedience orientation and the instrumental-relativist orientation. The next level, the conventional level, included the interpersonal concordance or \"good boy \u2013 nice girl\" orientation, along with the \"law and order\" orientation. Lastly, the final Postconventional level consisted of the social-contract, legalistic orientation and the universal-ethical-principle orientation.<ref>{{cite web|last=Crain|first=W.C.|title=Kohlberg's Stages of Moral Development |url=http://faculty.plts.edu/gpence/html/kohlberg.htm |work=Theories of Development |publisher=Prentice-Hall |accessdate=October 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004152005/http://faculty.plts.edu/gpence/html/kohlberg.htm |archivedate=October 4, 2011}}</ref> According to Kohlberg, an individual is considered more cognitively mature depending on their stage of moral reasoning, which grows as they advance in education and world experience.\n\nCritics of Kohlberg's approach (such as [[Carol Gilligan]] and Jane Attanucci) argue that there is an over-emphasis on [[justice]] and an under-emphasis on an additional perspective to moral reasoning, known as the [[Ethics of care|care perspective]]. The justice perspective draws attention to inequality and oppression, while striving for reciprocal rights and equal respect for all. The care perspective draws attention to the ideas of detachment and abandonment, while striving for attention and response to people who need it. Care Orientation is relationally based. It has a more situational focus that is dependent on the needs of others as opposed to Justice Orientation's objectivity.<ref name=\"Attanucci 1988\">{{cite book|title=Moral Development: Caring Voices and Women's Moral Frames|last1=Gilligan|first1=Carol|last2=Attanucci|first2=Jane|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1994|isbn=978-0-8153-1553-7|editor-last=Puka|editor-first=Bill|volume=34|location=|pages=123\u2013237|chapter=Two Moral Orientations: Gender Differences and Similarities|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_OBjzzmUS2oC&pg=PA123|issue=3}}</ref> However, reviews by others have found that Gilligan's theory was not supported by empirical studies since orientations are individual dependent.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Moral Development|last1=Walker|first1=Lawrence J.|last2=Smetana|first2=Judith|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2005|isbn=978-1-135-61917-6|editor-last=Killen|editor-first=Melanie|pages=93\u2013115|chapter=Gender and Morality|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=4CV5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA93}}</ref><ref>Jaffee and Hyde (2001){{Full citation needed|date=February 2018}}</ref> In fact, in neo-Kohlbergian studies with the Defining Issues Test, females tend to get slightly higher scores than males.<ref>{{cite book|title=Postconventional Moral Thinking: A Neo-Kohlbergian Approach|last1=Rest|first1=James R.|last2=Narvaez|first2=Darcia|last3=Thoma|first3=Stephen J.|last4=Bebeau|first4=Muriel J.|publisher=Psychology Press|year=1999|isbn=978-1-135-70561-9|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==== The attachment approach to moral judgment ====\nAner Govrin's attachment approach to moral judgment<ref>Govrin, A. (2014). The ABC of moral development: an attachment approach to moral judgment. Frontiers in psychology, 5 (6), 1-14. [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] This article contains quotations from this source, which is available under the [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/  Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported (CC BY 3.0)] license.</ref><ref>Govrin, A. (2019). Ethics and attachment - How we make moral judgments. London: Routledge</ref><ref>Govrin, A. (2014) \"From Ethics of Care to Psychology of Care: Reconnecting Ethics of Care to Contemporary Moral Psychology\", Frontiers in Psychology pp. 1-10</ref> proposes that, through early interactions with the caregiver, the child acquires an internal representation of a system of rules that determine how right/wrong judgments are to be construed, used, and understood. By breaking moral situations down into their defining features, the attachment model of moral judgment outlines a framework for a universal moral faculty based on a universal, innate, deep structure that appears uniformly in the structure of almost all moral judgments regardless of their content.\n\n===Moral behaviour===\n{{Also|Social preferences}}\n\nHistorically, major topics of study in the domain of moral behavior have included [[violence]] and [[altruism]],<ref name=\"Staub2003\">{{cite book |last1=Staub |first1=Ervin |title=Psychology of good and evil: why children, adults, and groups help and harm others. |date=2003 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-511-07031-0}}</ref> [[Bystander effect|bystander intervention]] and obedience to [[authority]] (e.g., the [[Milgram experiment]]<ref name=\"Milgram1963\">{{cite journal|last=Milgram |first=Stanley |year=1963 |title=Behavioral Study of Obedience |journal=Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology |volume=67 |issue=4 |pages=371\u20138 |pmid=14049516 |url=http://content.apa.org/journals/abn/67/4/371 |doi=10.1037/h0040525 |citeseerx=10.1.1.599.92 }}</ref> and [[Stanford prison experiment]]<ref name=\"Haney1972\">{{cite journal |last1=Haney |first1=Craig |last2=Banks |first2=Curtis |last3=Zimbardo |first3=Philip |title=Interpersonal Dynamics in a Simulated Prison |date=1972 |url=https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/751041.pdf}}</ref>).<ref name=\"Haidt&Kesebir2010\" /> Recent research on moral behavior uses a wide range of methods, including using [[Experience sampling method|experience sampling]] to try and estimate the actual prevalence of various kinds of moral behavior in everyday life.<ref name=\"Hofmann2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Hofmann |first1=W. |last2=Wisneski |first2=D. C. |last3=Brandt |first3=M. J. |last4=Skitka |first4=L. J. |title=Morality in everyday life |journal=Science |date=11 September 2014 |volume=345 |issue=6202 |pages=1340\u20131343 |doi=10.1126/science.1251560|pmid=25214626 |bibcode=2014Sci...345.1340H }}</ref><ref name=\"Hofmann2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Hofmann |first1=Wilhelm |last2=Brandt |first2=Mark J. |last3=Wisneski |first3=Daniel C. |last4=Rockenbach |first4=Bettina |last5=Skitka |first5=Linda J. |title=Moral Punishment in Everyday Life |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin |date=30 May 2018 |volume=44 |issue=12 |pages=1697\u20131711 |doi=10.1177/0146167218775075|pmid=29848212 |url=https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/files/25376159/Moral_Punishment_in_Everyday_Life.pdf }}</ref> Research has also focused on variation in moral behavior over time, through studies of phenomena such as [[Self-licensing|moral licensing]].<ref name=monin>{{cite journal | last1 = Monin | first1 = B | last2 = Miller | first2 = D. T. | year = 2001 | title = Moral credentials and the expression of prejudice | journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology | volume = 81 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201343 | pmid = 11474723 | doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.81.1.33 | url = http://www.ask-force.org/web/Discourse/Monin-Moral-Credentials-Prejudice-2001.pdf | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150430050738/http://www.ask-force.org/web/Discourse/Monin-Moral-Credentials-Prejudice-2001.pdf | archivedate = 2015-04-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"Blanken2015\">{{cite journal |last1=Blanken |first1=Irene |last2=van de Ven |first2=Niels |last3=Zeelenberg |first3=Marcel |title=A Meta-Analytic Review of Moral Licensing |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin |date=25 February 2015 |volume=41 |issue=4 |pages=540\u2013558 |doi=10.1177/0146167215572134|pmid=25716992 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/57dc276cb749a78930b609f0d016601ab5b379bf }}</ref> Yet other studies focusing on social preferences examine various kinds of resource allocation decisions,<ref name=\"Henrich2005\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peysakhovich |first1=Alexander |last2=Nowak |first2=Martin A. |last3=Rand |first3=David G. |title=Humans display a \u2018cooperative phenotype\u2019 that is domain general and temporally stable |journal=Nature Communications |date=16 September 2014 |volume=5 |issue=1 |doi=10.1038/ncomms5939|doi-access=free }}</ref> or use incentivized beavioral experiments to investigate the way people weight their own interests against other people's when deciding whether to harm others, for example, by examine how willing people are to administer electric shocks to themselves vs. others in exchange for money.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Crockett |first1=Molly J. |last2=Kurth-Nelson |first2=Zeb |last3=Siegel |first3=Jenifer Z. |last4=Dayan |first4=Peter |last5=Dolan |first5=Raymond J. |title=Harm to others outweighs harm to self in moral decision making |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=2 December 2014 |volume=111 |issue=48 |pages=17320\u201317325 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1408988111|pmid=25404350 |pmc=4260587 |bibcode=2014PNAS..11117320C }}</ref>\n\nJames Rest reviewed the literature on moral functioning and identified at least four components necessary for a moral behavior to take place:<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rest|first=James R|date=1983|title=Morality|journal=Handbook of Child Psychology|volume=3|pages=556\u2013629}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Narv\u00e1ez|first1=Darcia|last2=Rest|first2=James|date=1995|title=The four components of acting morally|url=https://www3.nd.edu/~dnarvaez/documents/NARVAEZREST.pdf|journal=Moral Behavior and Moral Development: An Introduction|volume=|pages=385\u2013400|via=}}</ref>\n* Sensitivity \u2013 noticing and interpreting the situation\n* Reasoning and making a judgment regarding the best (most moral) option\n* Motivation (in the moment but also habitually, such as moral identity)\n* implementation\u2014having the skills and perseverance to carry out the action\nReynolds and Ceranic researched the effects of social consensus on one's moral behavior. Depending on the level of social consensus (high vs. low), moral behaviors will require greater or lesser degrees of moral identity to motivate an individual to make a choice and endorse a behavior. Also, depending on social consensus, particular behaviors may require different levels of moral reasoning.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reynolds|first1=Scott J.|last2=Ceranic|first2=Tara L.|date=2007|title=The effects of moral judgment and moral identity on moral behavior: An empirical examination of the moral individual.|url=http://www.pauldavidtuff.com/PDF%20Files/Effects_of_Moral_Judgement.pdf|journal=Journal of Applied Psychology|volume=92|issue=6|pages=1610\u20131624|doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.6.1610|pmid=18020800|issn=1939-1854}}</ref>\n\nMore recent attempts to develop an integrated model of moral motivation<ref>{{cite journal|last=Leffel|first=G. M.|date=2008|title=Who cares? Generativity and the moral emotions, part 2: A \"social intuitionist model\" of moral motivation|url=|journal=Journal of Psychology and Theology|volume=36|issue=3|pages=182\u2013201|ref=harv|doi=10.1177/009164710803600303}}</ref> have identified at least six different levels of moral functioning, each of which has been shown to predict some type of moral or pro-social behavior: moral intuitions, moral emotions, moral virtues/vices (behavioral capacities), moral values, moral reasoning, and moral willpower. This [[Social intuitionism|social intuitionist]] model of moral motivation<ref>{{harvnb|Leffel|2008}}'s model draws heavily on {{harvnb|Haidt|2001}}'s social intuitionist model of moral judgment.</ref> suggests that moral behaviors are typically the product of multiple levels of moral functioning, and are usually energized by the \"hotter\" levels of intuition, emotion, and behavioral virtue/vice. The \"cooler\" levels of values, reasoning, and willpower, while still important, are proposed to be secondary to the more affect-intensive processes.\n\nMoral behavior is also studied under the umbrella of [[personality psychology]] where it is described in terms of traits such as [[agreeableness]], [[cooperativeness]] and [[Honesty-humility factor of the HEXACO model of personality|honesty/humility]].<ref name=\"Thielmann2020\">{{cite journal |last1=Thielmann |first1=Isabel |last2=Spadaro |first2=Giuliana |last3=Balliet |first3=Daniel |title=Personality and prosocial behavior: A theoretical framework and meta-analysis. |journal=Psychological Bulletin |date=January 2020 |volume=146 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201390 |doi=10.1037/bul0000217}}</ref>\n\n====Value-behavior consistency====\n{{Also|Moral disengagement}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2019}}\nIn looking at the relations between moral values, attitudes, and behaviors, previous research asserts that there is no dependable correlation between these three aspects, differing from what we would assume. In fact, it seems to be more common for people to label their behaviors with a justifying value rather than having a value beforehand and then acting on it. There are some people that are more likely to act on their personal values: those low in self-monitoring and high in self-consciousness, due to the fact that they are more aware of themselves and less aware of how others may perceive them. Self-consciousness here means being literally more conscious of yourself, not fearing judgement or feeling anxiety from others. Social situations and the different categories of norms can be telling of when people may act in accordance with their values, but this still isn't concrete either. People will typically act in accordance with social, contextual and personal norms, and there is a likelihood that these norms can also follow one's moral values. Though there are certain assumptions and situations that would suggest a major value-attitude-behavior relation, there is not enough research to confirm this phenomenon.\n\n====Moral willpower====\n{{Main|Ego depletion|Self-control}}\n{{See also|Delayed gratification|Social cognitive theory of morality}}\nBuilding on earlier work by Metcalfe and [[Walter Mischel#Self-control|Mischel]] on delayed gratification,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal|last1=Metcalfe|first1=J.|last2=Mischel|first2=W.|year=1999|title=A hot/cool-system analysis of delay of gratification: Dynamics of willpower|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/13101564|journal=Psychological Review|volume=106|issue=1|pages=3\u201319|doi=10.1037/0033-295x.106.1.3|pmid=10197361|via=}}</ref> Baumeister, Miller, and Delaney explored the notion of willpower by first defining the self as being made up of three parts: reflexive consciousness, or the person's awareness of their environment and of himself as an individual; interpersonal being, which seeks to mold the self into one that will be accepted by others; and executive function.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite book|title=Judeo-Christian Perspectives on Psychology: Human Nature, Motivation, and Change|last=Baumeister|publisher=American Psychological Association|year=2005|isbn=978-1-59147-161-5|editor-last=Miller|editor-first=William|location=Washington, DC|pages=57\u201372|chapter=Self and volition|ref=harv|editor-last2=Delaney|editor-first2=Harold}}</ref> They stated, \"[T]he self can free its actions from being determined by particular influences, especially those of which it is aware\".{{Sfn|Baumeister|2005|p=68}} The three prevalent theories of willpower describe it as a limited supply of energy, as a cognitive process, and as a skill that is developed over time. Research has largely supported that willpower works like a \"moral muscle\" with a limited supply of strength that may be depleted (a process referred to as Ego depletion), conserved, or replenished, and that a single act requiring much self-control can significantly deplete the \"supply\" of willpower.<ref name=\":4\" /> While exertion reduces the ability to engage in further acts of willpower in the short term, such exertions actually improve a person's ability to exert willpower for extended periods in the long run.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Muraven|first1=Mark|last2=Baumeister|first2=Roy F.|last3=Tice|first3=Dianne M.|date=August 1, 1999|title=Longitudinal Improvement of Self-Regulation Through Practice: Building Self-Control Strength Through Repeated Exercise|url=https://www.albany.edu/~muraven/publications/promotion%20files/articles/muraven,%20baumeister,%20&%20tice,%201999.pdf|journal=The Journal of Social Psychology|volume=139|issue=4|pages=446\u2013457|doi=10.1080/00224549909598404|issn=0022-4545|pmid=10457761}}</ref> Additional research has been conducted that may [[Ego depletion#Reproducibility controversy and conflicting meta analyses|cast doubt on the idea of ego-depletion]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/c17hie7wh4yaohd/Hagger%20et%20al%20%282016%29%20A%20Multilab%20Preregistered%20Replication%20of%20the%20Ego-Depletion%20Effect.pdf?dl=0 | title=Hagger et al (2016) A Multilab Preregistered Replication of the Ego-Depletion Effect.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Moral intuitions===\n{{Main|Social intuitionism|Dual process theory (moral psychology)}}\nIn 2001, Jonathan Haidt introduced his [[Social intuitionism|social intuitionist model]]<nowiki/> which claimed that with few exceptions, moral judgments are made based upon socially derived intuitions. Moral intuitions happen immediately, automatically, and [[Unconscious mind|unconsciously]], with reasoning largely serving to generate post-hoc rationalizations to justify one's instinctual reactions.<ref name=\"Haidt2001\" /> He provides four arguments to doubt causal importance of reason. Firstly, Haidt argues that since there is a [[Dual process theory|dual process system]] in the brain when making automatic evaluations or assessments, this same process must be applicable to moral judgement as well. The second argument, based on research on [[motivated reasoning]], claims that people behave like \"intuitive lawyers\", searching primarily for evidence that will serve motives for social relatedness and attitudinal coherence. Thirdly, Haidt found that people have post hoc reasoning when faced with a moral situation, this a posteriori (after the fact) explanation gives the illusion of objective moral judgement but in reality is subjective to one's gut feeling. Lastly, research has shown that moral emotion has a stronger link to moral action than moral reasoning, citing Damasio's research on the [[somatic marker hypothesis]] and Batson's [[empathy-altruism]] hypothesis.<ref name=\"Haidt2001\" />\n\nFollowing the publication of a landmark fMRI study in 2001,<ref name=\"Greene2001\" /> [[Joshua Greene (psychologist)|Joshua Greene]] proposed his [[Dual process theory (moral psychology)|dual process theory of moral judgment]], according to which intuitive/emotional and deliberative processes respectively give rise to characteristically deontological and consequentialist moral judgments. A \"[[Deontological ethics|deontologist]]\" is someone who has rule-based morality that is mainly focused on duties and rights; in contrast, a \"[[Consequentialism|consequentialist]]\" is someone who believes that only the best overall consequences ultimately matter.<ref>{{cite book|title=Moral Psychology|last=Greene|first=Joshua|publisher=MIT Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-262-69355-4|editor-last=Sinnott-Armstrong|editor-first=Walter|volume=3|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=35\u201380|chapter=The secret joke of Kant\u2019s Soul|oclc=750463100}}</ref> Generally speaking, individuals who answer to moral dilemmas in a consequential manner take longer to respond and show [[Frontal lobe|frontal-lobe]] activity (associated with cognitive processing). Individuals who answer to moral dilemmas in a deontological manner, however, generally answer more quickly and show brain activity in the [[amygdala]] (associated with emotional processing).\n\n===Moral emotions===\n{{Main|Moral emotions}}\n{{See also|Social emotions}}\nMoral emotions are a variety of social emotion that are involved in forming and communicating moral judgments and decisions, and in motivating behavioral responses to one's own and others' moral behavior.<ref name=\"Pizarro2007b\">{{cite book |last1=Pizarro |first1=David A. |editor1-last=Baumeister |editor1-first=Roy F |editor2-last=Vohs |editor2-first=Kathleen D |title=Encyclopedia of Social Psychology |date=2007 |publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc. |isbn=9781412956253 |pages=588\u2013589 |chapter=Moral Emotions|doi=10.4135/9781412956253.n350 }}</ref><ref name=\"Haidt, J. 2003 p. 855\">{{cite book|title=Handbook of Affective Sciences|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-19-512601-3|editor-last=Davidson|editor-first=Richard|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookofaffect0000unse/page/855 855]|chapter=The Moral Emotions|ref=harv|editor-last2=Scherer|editor-first2=Klaus|editor-last3=Goldsmith|editor-first3=H.|chapter-url=http://www.gruberpeplab.com/teaching/psych3131_spring2015/documents/4.1_Haidt2003_Moralemotions.pdf|url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofaffect0000unse/page/855}}</ref><ref name=\"Tangney2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Tangney |first1=June Price |last2=Stuewig |first2=Jeff |last3=Mashek |first3=Debra J. |title=Moral Emotions and Moral Behavior |journal=Annual Review of Psychology |date=January 2007 |volume=58 |issue=1 |pages=345\u2013372 |doi=10.1146/annurev.psych.56.091103.070145 |pmid=16953797 |pmc=3083636 |url=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~squartz/Tangney.pdf}}</ref>\nWhile moral reasoning has been the focus of most study of morality dating all the way back to Plato and Aristotle, the emotive side of morality has been looked upon with disdain.<ref name=\"Pizarro2007b\" /> However, in the last 30\u201340 years, there has been a rise in a new front of research: moral emotions as the basis for moral behavior. This development began with a focus on [[empathy]] and [[Guilt (emotion)|guilt]], but has since moved on to encompass new scholarship on emotions such as [[anger]], [[shame]], [[disgust]], [[awe]], and [[elevation]]. With the new research, theorists have begun to question whether moral emotions might hold a larger in determining morality, one that might even surpass that of moral reasoning.<ref name=\"Haidt, J. 2003 p. 855\" />\n\n===Moralization and moral conviction===\n\nMoralization, a term introduced to moral psychology by [[Paul Rozin]], refers to the process through which preferences are converted into values.<ref name=\"Rozin1999\">{{cite journal |last1=Rozin |first1=Paul |title=The Process of Moralization |journal=Psychological Science |date=1999 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=218\u2013221 |doi=10.1111/1467-9280.00139}}</ref><ref name=\"Rozin1997\">{{cite journal |last1=Rozin |first1=Paul |last2=Markwith |first2=Maureen |last3=Stoess |first3=Caryn |title=Moralization and Becoming a Vegetarian: The Transformation of Preferences Into Values and the Recruitment of Disgust |journal=Psychological Science |date=6 May 2016 |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=67\u201373 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-9280.1997.tb00685.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Rhee2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Rhee |first1=Joshua J. |last2=Schein |first2=Chelsea |last3=Bastian |first3=Brock |title=The what, how, and why of moralization: A review of current definitions, methods, and evidence in moralization research |journal=Social and Personality Psychology Compass |date=25 November 2019 |volume=13 |issue=12 |doi=10.1111/spc3.12511}}</ref> Relatedly, [[Linda Skitka]] and colleagues have introduced the concept of moral conviction, which refers to a \"strong and absolute belief that something is right or wrong, moral or immoral.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Skitka|first=Linda|year=2002|title=Do the means always justify the ends or do the ends sometimes justify the means? A value protection model of justice|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247746696|journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin|volume=28|issue=5|pages=452\u2013461|doi=10.1177/0146167202288003|via=}}</ref> According to Skitka's integrated theory of moral conviction (ITMC), attitudes held with moral conviction, known as moral mandates, differ from strong but non-moral attitudes in a number of important ways. Namely, moral mandates derive their motivational force from their perceived universality, perceived objectivity, and strong ties to emotion.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Peace Psychology|last=Morgan|first=G. S.|last2=Skitka|first2=L. J.|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4051-9644-4|editor=Christie|editor-first=Daniel J.|location=|pages=|chapter=Moral conviction}}</ref> Perceived universality refers to the notion that individuals experience moral mandates as transcending persons and cultures; additionally, they are regarded as matters of fact. Regarding association with emotion, ITMC is consistent with Jonathan Haidt's social intuitionist model in stating that moral judgments are accompanied by discrete moral emotions (i.e., disgust, shame, guilt). Importantly, Skitka maintains that moral mandates are not the same thing as moral values. Whether an issue will be associated with moral conviction varies across persons.\n\nOne of the main lines of IMTC research addresses the behavioral implications of moral mandates. Individuals prefer greater social and physical distance from attitudinally dissimilar others when moral conviction was high. This effect of moral conviction could not be explained by traditional measures of attitude strength, extremity, or centrality. Skitka, Bauman, and Sargis placed participants in either attitudinally heterogeneous or homogenous groups to discuss procedures regarding two morally mandated issues, [[abortion]] and [[capital punishment]]. Those in attitudinally heterogeneous groups demonstrated the least amount of goodwill towards other group members, the least amount of cooperation, and the most tension/defensiveness. Furthermore, individuals discussing a morally mandated issue were less likely to reach a consensus compared to those discussing non-moral issues.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Skitka|first=L. J.|author2=Bauman, C.|author3=Sargis, E.|year=2005|title=Moral conviction: Another contributor to attitude strength or something more?|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/7e7e/2fb7cf672e00b4ea00b4a75d4eee2fd51f5d.pdf|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=88|issue=6|pages=895\u2013917|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.88.6.895|pmid=15982112|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Intersections with other fields==\n===Sociological applications===\nSome research shows that people tend to self-segregate based on moral or moral-political values.<ref name=Haidt2003>{{cite journal | last = Haidt | first = Jonathan | last2 = Rosenberg | first2 = Evan | last3 = Hom | first3 = Holly | year = 2003 | title = Differentiating Diversities: Moral Diversity Is Not Like Other Kinds | journal = Journal of Applied Social Psychology | volume = 33 | issue =1 | pages = 1\u201336 | doi=10.1111/j.1559-1816.2003.tb02071.x}}</ref><ref name=Motyl2014>{{cite journal | last1 = Motyl | first1 = Matt | last2 = Iyer | first2 = Ravi | last3 = Oishi | first3 = Shigehiro | last4 = Trawalterl | first4 = Sophie | last5 = Nosek | first5 = Brian A. | year = 2014 | title = How ideological migration geographically segregates groups | journal = Journal of Experimental Social Psychology | volume = 51 | pages = 1\u201314 | doi=10.1016/j.jesp.2013.10.010| url = http://psyarxiv.com/25myb/ }}</ref>\n\n===Normative implications===\nResearchers have begun to debate the implications (if any) moral psychology research has for other subfields of ethics such as [[normative ethics]] and [[meta-ethics]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kahane |first1=Guy |title=Evolutionary Debunking Arguments |journal=No\u00fbs |date=March 2011 |volume=45 |issue=1 |pages=103\u2013125 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-0068.2010.00770.x|pmid=21949447 |pmc=3175808 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Joshua |title=From neural 'is' to moral 'ought': what are the moral implications of neuroscientific moral psychology? |journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience |date=October 2003 |volume=4 |issue=10 |pages=846\u2013850 |doi=10.1038/nrn1224}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Joshua |last2=Cohen |first2=Jonathan |title=For the law, neuroscience changes nothing and everything |journal= Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B: Biological Sciences|date=29 November 2004 |volume=359 |issue=1451 |pages=1775\u20131785 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2004.1546|pmid=15590618 |pmc=1693457 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berker |first1=Selim |title=The Normative Insignificance of Neuroscience |journal=Philosophy & Public Affairs |date=September 2009 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=293\u2013329 |doi=10.1111/j.1088-4963.2009.01164.x|url=http://nrs.harvard.edu/urn-3:HUL.InstRepos:4391332 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nagel |first1=Thomas |title=You Can't Learn About Morality from Brain Scans |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/115279/joshua-greenes-moral-tribes-reviewed-thomas-nagel |website=The New Republic |date=2 November 2013}}</ref> For example [[Peter Singer]], citing Haidt's work on social intuitionism and Greene's dual process theory, has suggested that the normative force of our moral intuitions is undermined by their being the \"biological residue of our evolutionary history.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Singer |first1=Peter |title=Ethics and Intuitions |journal=The Journal of Ethics |date=October 2005 |volume=9 |issue=3-4 |pages=331\u2013352 |doi=10.1007/s10892-005-3508-y}}</ref> John Doris discusses the way in which [[Social psychology|social psychological]] experiments\u2014such as the [[Stanford prison experiment]]s involving the idea of [[Situationism (psychology)|situationism]]\u2014call into question a key component in [[virtue ethics]]: the idea that individuals have a single, environment-independent moral character.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lack of Character: Personality and Moral Behavior|last=Doris|first=John M.|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-316-02549-9|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=February 2018}} As a further example, [[Shaun Nichols]] (2004) examines how empirical data on psychopathology suggests that [[moral rationalism]] is false.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sentimental Rules: On the Natural Foundations of Moral Judgment|last=Nichols|first=Shaun|date=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-988347-9|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nAdditionally, research in moral psychology is being used to inform debates in applied ethics around [[moral enhancement]].<ref name=\"Darby2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Darby |first1=R. Ryan |last2=Pascual-Leone |first2=Alvaro |title=Moral Enhancement Using Non-invasive Brain Stimulation |journal=Frontiers in Human Neuroscience |date=22 February 2017 |volume=11 |pages=77 |doi=10.3389/fnhum.2017.00077|pmid=28275345 |pmc=5319982 }}</ref><ref name=\"Levy2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Levy |first1=Neil |last2=Douglas |first2=Thomas |last3=Kahane |first3=Guy |last4=Terbeck |first4=Sylvia |last5=Cowen |first5=Philip J. |last6=Hewstone |first6=Miles |last7=Savulescu |first7=Julian |title=Are You Morally Modified?: The Moral Effects of Widely Used Pharmaceuticals |journal=Philosophy, Psychiatry, & Psychology |date=2014 |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=111\u2013125 |doi=10.1353/ppp.2014.0023|pmid=25892904 |pmc=4398979 }}</ref>\n\n===Robotics and artificial intelligence===\n{{Main|Machine ethics}}\n{{See also|Robot ethics|Ethics of artificial intelligence}}\nAt the intersection of moral psychology and machine ethics, researchers have begun to study people's views regarding the potentially ethically significant decisions that will be made by [[self-driving car]]s.<ref name=\"Bonnefon2016\" /><ref name=\"Awad2018\" /><ref name=\"Awad2020\">{{cite journal |last1=Awad |first1=Edmond |last2=Dsouza |first2=Sohan |last3=Bonnefon |first3=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |last4=Shariff |first4=Azim |last5=Rahwan |first5=Iyad |title=Crowdsourcing moral machines |journal=Communications of the ACM |date=24 February 2020 |volume=63 |issue=3 |pages=48\u201355 |doi=10.1145/3339904|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n* [[Action (philosophy)]]\n* [[Agency (philosophy)]]\n* [[Altruism]]\n* [[Character education]]\n* [[Descriptive ethics]]\n* [[Experimental philosophy]]\n* [[Internalism and externalism#Moral philosophy|Internalism and externalism \u00a7Moral philosophy]]\n* [[List of ethics topics]]\n* [[Meta-ethics]]\n* [[Moral luck]]\n* [[Neuroethics]]\n* [[Neuroeconomics#Social decision making|Neuroeconomics \u00a7Social decision making]]\n* [[Personal identity]]\n* [[Psychological egoism]]\n* [[Science of morality]]\n* [[Social preferences]]\n* [[Trolley problem]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n*{{cite journal|last1=Baron|first1=J.|last2=Spranca|first2=M.|year=1997|title=Protected values|url=|journal=Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes|volume=70|issue=1|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1006/obhd.1997.2690|pmid=9236161}}\n*{{cite book|last=Batson|first=Charles Daniel|title=The Altruism Question: Toward a Social Psychological Answer|year=1991|publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum Associates|isbn=978-0-8058-0245-0|location=Hillsdale, New Jersey|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last=Brandt|first=Allan M.|title=Unfiltered: Conflicts Over Tobacco Policy and Public Health|editor-last=Feldman|editor-first=Eric|editor-last2=Bayer|editor-first2=Ronald|chapter=Difference and diffusion: Cross-cultural perspectives on the rise of anti-tobacco policies|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|year=2004|pages=255\u2013380|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn